lostridium difficile","Giardia lamblia","Salmonella typhi","Tropheryma whipplei","Vibrio cholerae"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGiardia lamblia\u003C/strong\u003E is a protozoan parasite that commonly causes malabsorption by adhering to the small intestinal villi and causing villous atrophy. This leads to decreased absorption surface area and enzyme deficiencies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETropheryma whipplei\u003C/strong\u003E can cause malabsorption in Whipple disease but is extremely rare. \u003Cstrong\u003ESalmonella typhi\u003C/strong\u003E primarily causes systemic infection and typhoid fever. \u003Cstrong\u003EVibrio cholerae\u003C/strong\u003E causes severe secretory diarrhoea but not malabsorption. \u003Cstrong\u003EClostridium difficile\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects the large bowel and does not typically cause small bowel malabsorption.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Giardia lamblia is a protozoan parasite that causes malabsorption by adhering to and damaging small intestinal villi","Whipple disease, caused by Tropheryma whipplei, is a rare bacterial infection causing malabsorption","Coeliac disease is a non-infectious cause of malabsorption"],"references":["Baker S, The HC. Recent insights into Shigella. Curr Opin Infect Dis. 2018 Oct;31(5):449-454. doi: 10.1097/QCO.0000000000000475. PMID: 30048255; PMCID: PMC6143181.","Leung AKC, Leung AAM, Wong AHC, Sergi CM, Kam JKM. Giardiasis: An Overview. Recent Pat Inflamm Allergy Drug Discov. 2019;13(2):134-143. doi: 10.2174/1872213X13666190618124901. PMID: 31210116.","Thomson AB, Keelan M, Thiesen A, Clandinin MT, Ropeleski M, Wild GE. Small bowel review: diseases of the small intestine. Dig Dis Sci. 2001 Dec;46(12):2555-66. doi: 10.1023/a:1012782321827. PMID: 11768246.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of